{"cursor":"17514","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox book \n| name = The Jungle image = caption = 1st edition author = Upton Sinclair\n| country = United States language = English genre = Political fiction\n| publisher = Doubleday, Jabber & Company release_date = February 26, 1906\n| media_type = Print (Hardcover) pages = 475 isbn =  oclc = 149214\n}}\n\n'The Jungle' is a 1906 novel written by the American journalist and novelist\nUpton Sinclair (1878â1968). Sinclair wrote the novel to portray the\nlives of immigrants in the United States. Many readers were most concerned with\nhis exposure of practices in the American meatpacking industry during the early\n20th century, based on an investigation he did for a socialist newspaper.\n\nThe book depicts poverty, the absence of social programs, unpleasant living and\nworking conditions, and the hopelessness prevalent among the working class,\nwhich is contrasted with the deeply rooted corruption of people in power. A\nreview by the writer Jack London called it, \"the [[Uncle Tom's Cabin]] of wage\nslavery.\" [http://www.socalhistory.org/bios/upton_sinclair.html \"Upton\nSinclair\"], Social History blog\n\nSinclair was considered a muckraker, or journalist who exposed corruption in\ngovernment and business. Sinclair, Upton. The Jungle, Dover Thrift Editions,\nNote: pages viii-x He first published the novel in serial form in 1905 in\nthe socialist newspaper, [[Appeal to Reason (newspaper)|Appeal to Reason]],\nbetween February 25, 1905, and November 4, 1905. In 1904, Sinclair had spent\nseven weeks in 1904 gathering information while working incognito in the\nmeatpacking plants of the Chicago stockyards for the newspaper. It was published\nas a book on 26 February 1906 by Doubleday and in a subscribers'\nedition. Gottesman, Ronald. Introduction to Penguin Classics edition of the\nnovel.\n\nA film version of the novel was made in 1914, but it has since become lost.\n","linknr":260,"url":"The_Jungle","recorded":1376427790,"links":["/w/index.php?title=The_Jungle&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=The_Jungle&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Jungle","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Jungle_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:TheJungleSinclair.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/53/TheJungleSinclair.jpg/200px-TheJungleSinclair.jpg","/wiki/Upton_Sinclair","/wiki/Political_fiction","/wiki/Doubleday_(publisher)","/wiki/Hardcover","/wiki/OCLC","http://worldcat.org/oclc/149214","/wiki/Journalist","/wiki/Novelist","/wiki/Upton_Sinclair","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Immigrants","/wiki/Political_corruption","/wiki/Jack_London","/wiki/Uncle_Tom%27s_Cabin","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Muckraker","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Appeal_to_Reason_(newspaper)","/wiki/Doubleday_(publisher)","#cite_note-4","/wiki/The_Jungle_(1914_film)","/wiki/Lost_film","#Plot_summary","#Characters","#Publication_history","#Reception","#Federal_response","#Continuing_interest","#Adaptations","#Footnotes","#Further_reading","#External_links","/w/index.php?title=The_Jungle&action=edit&section=